Equity markets in Europe cheered a move by the U.S. and the European Union to defuse trade tensions, which investors and analysts see as an encouraging sign for tariff-hit stocks while also noting that negotiations are just beginning. The Stoxx 600 automobiles & parts index gained as much as 2.3 percent after President Donald Trump and European Commission President Jean-Claude Juncker agreed to put car tariffs on hold. The auto sector plunged 2.9 percent on Wednesday after Fiat Chrysler Automobiles NV and General Motors Co. both reduced their guidance. Here’s what investors and analysts had to say about the latest tariff developments. Read more on the U.S./EU ceasefire in their trade spat: Carmakers Surge After Trump Agrees to Put Auto Tariffs on Hold — With assistance by Jan-Patrick Barnert, Justina Lee, and Ksenia Galouchko